Customer reviews

Customer reviews4.3 out of 5 stars864.3 out of 5 stars5 star55%4 star31%3 star8%2 star5%1 star1%ForsakenbyJames David JordanFormat: Paperback|ChangePrice:$2.99+ $3.99 shippingWrite a reviewAdd to CartAdd to Wish List
This page works best with JavaScript. Disabling it will result in some disabled or missing features. You can still see all customer reviews for the product.


Top positive reviewSee all 74 positive reviews› 4.0 out of 5 starsWell done, great characters, high quality writing and a plot that seems familiar and recycled but definitely isn't.ByJTon November 9, 2014This was a great twist on the usual spy thriller genre that I enjoy.  A former CIA agent, flawed in so many ways, you think you have read about this character before...but you haven't.No, not a grizzled old veteran of the spy game off to ensure justice in some secret mission from the POTUS.  Nope, not a superstar-ninja-cannot be defeated by any means FBI agent seeking justice for some unsolved crime.This may have had some "standard" character and plot ideas, but the heroine is far from your standard spy thriller fare.  She's flawed, she makes mistakes, but what keeps her from being just another cliche ex CIA agent is the great character Jordan has created.  First, just the simple fact that she's a she.  Then the pertinent fact that she doesn't *always* win.  Finally, the great writing that creates the character and draws you in slowly, patiently, all the while building not to a climax regarding the supposed mystery happening around her, but the full on resolution of just how she came to be who she is.I won't do any spoiler alerts, but you will be surprised when the plot twists.  Usually, if you are a fan of spy thrillers like myself, you can predict the "twist" by the second chapter.Never saw this one coming.

Read more
Top critical reviewSee all 12 critical reviews› 
          One person found this helpful
3.0 out of 5 starsA novel with good characters, but boringByBill Garrisonon August 31, 2013David Jordan James' FORSAKEN is a Christian drama that starts out thrilling and suspenseful, but turns into a character driven story about faith and the choices a person must make. Taken together the two elements don't work well together. I wish the author had been more consistent with genre.Taylor Pasbury is a 29 year old former secret service agent who now runs a nationally recognized security firm. The novel opens with a tragic event occurred when she was 18, and shaped her life for the next several years. The author then tells us of Taylor's habits of drinking a lot and sleeping around. It made for an interesting character, but wasn't as powerful as it could have been, because it was told, and not shown.Simon Mason is a world famous evangelist who fills arenas everywhere and has the heart of Billy Graham. He hires Taylor to be his own security consultant, and her first night on the job, tragedy strikes. That event shakes Simon's life, and his faith.Unfortunately, for the rest of the novel, nothing really happens. There is the hint of characters forming bonds but nothing really happens. Taylor makes moves to get past the demons that haunt her. Simon battles his faith...and well that's it. I wish there had been more character development and twists, but that all happens at the end of the novel, and by then it is too late.

Read more



